18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 47 O.S. 2021, Section 11-314, as
19 amended by Section 1, Chapter 270, O.S.L. 2023 (47 O.S. Supp. 2023,
20 Section 11-314), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 11-314. A. This section shall be known and may be
22 cited as the “Bernardo-Mills Law”.
23 B. The driver of a motor vehicle, upon approaching a stationary
24 authorized emergency vehicle, a Department of Transportation
Req. No. 10281 Page 1

1 main tenance vehicle, a Turnpike Authority maintenance vehicle, a
2 stationary vehicle that is displaying flashing lights or a licensed
3 wrecker that is displaying a flashing amber light, a combination red
4 or blue light or any combination of amber, red or blue lights,
5 shall:
6 1. If traveling on a highway that consists of two or more lanes
7 that carry traffic in the same direction of travel as that of the
8 driver, the driver shall proceed with due caution and shall, if
9 possible and with due regard to the road, weather, and traffic
10 conditions, change lanes into a lane that is not adjacent to the
11 stationary authorized emergency vehicle, a Department of
12 Transportation maintenance vehicle, a Turnpike Authority maintenance
13 vehicle, or licensed wrecker; or if the driver is not able to change
14 lanes or if to do so would be unsafe, the driver shall proceed with
15 due caution and reduce the speed of the motor vehicle to a safe
16 speed that is below the posted speed limit; and
17 2. If traveling on a highway other than a highway described in
18 paragraph 1 of this subsection, the driver shall proceed with due
19 caution and reduce the speed of the motor vehicle to a safe speed
20 that is below the posted speed limit.
21 A person shall be guilty of the offense of roadway endangerment
22 of an emergency worker, upon conviction, for any offense act or
23 omission committed in violation of this subsection.
24
Req. No. 10281 Page 2

1 C. This section does not relieve the operator of a stationary
2 authorized emergency vehicle, a Department of Transportation
3 maintenance vehicle, a Turnpike Authority maintenance vehicle, or
4 licensed wrecker from the consequences of reckless disregard for the
5 safety of all persons and property upon the highway.
6 D. Upon conviction for committing the offense of roadway
7 endangerment of an emergency worker pursuant to subsection B of this
8 section, if no injury or death of an emergency worker individual
9 resulted from the offense, and in addition to any other penalty
10 authorized by law, the person shall be subject to a fine of:
11 1. One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00) for a first offense; and
12 2. Two Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00) for a second
13 offense.
14 A person committing a first offense in violation of this
15 subsection may complete the Operation Work Zone Awareness program
16 established in Section 11-1304 of this title to avoid the monetary
17 penalty of a first offense.
18 E. A person shall be deemed to commit the offense of aggravated
19 roadway endangerment of an emergency worker upon conviction for any
20 offense pursuant to act or omission constituting an offense under
21 subsection B of this section when such offense results in the injury
22 or death of an emergency worker individual. Upon conviction for
23 committing the offense of aggravated roadway endangerment of an
24 emergency worker, in addition to any other penalty authorized by
Req. No. 10281 Page 3

1 law, the person shall be subject to a fine of not more than Five
2 Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00) if the offense resulted in injury to an
3 emergency worker and not more than Ten Thousand Dollars ($10,000.00)
4 if the offense resulted in the death of an emergency worker
5 individual.
6 F. No person shall be cited or convicted for roadway
7 endangerment of an emergency worker or aggravated roadway
8 endangerment of an emergency worker for any act or omission
9 otherwise constituting an offense under subsection B of this section
10 if such act or omission resulted, in whole or in part, from
11 mechanical failure of the vehicle of the person or from the
12 negligence of another person or an emergency worker.
13 G. As used in this section, the term “stationary vehicle” shall
14 include, but may not be limited to, any: stationary vehicle;
15 authorized emergency vehicle; Department of Transportation
16 maintenance vehicle; Oklahoma Turnpike Authority maintenance
17 vehicle; service vehicle belonging to a utility company; or licensed
18 wrecker that is displaying flashing amber lights, a combination of
19 red or blue lights, or any combination of amber, red, or blue
20 lights.
